# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1903-new-york-highlanders-season
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1903-new-york-highlanders-season/1903-boston-americans-season] The **1903 Boston Americans season** was the third season for the professional baseball franchise that later became known as the Boston Red Sox.
[src:1903-new-york-highlanders-season/1903-boston-americans-season] The Americans finished first in the American League (AL) with a record of 91 wins and 47 losses, 14+1⁄2 games ahead of the Philadelphia Athletics.
[src:1903-new-york-highlanders-season/1903-boston-americans-season] Boston went on to participate in the first World Series held between the AL and National League (NL) champions.
[src:1903-new-york-highlanders-season/1903-boston-americans-season] The Americans won the 1903 World Series in eight games over the Pittsburgh Pirates.
[src:1903-new-york-highlanders-season/1903-boston-americans-season] The team was managed by Jimmy Collins and played its home games at Huntington Avenue Grounds.
[src:1903-new-york-highlanders-season/1903-boston-americans-season] Prior to the regular season, the team held spring training in Macon, Georgia.
[src:1903-new-york-highlanders-season/1903-boston-americans-season] Cy Young was a coach for the Mercer University baseball team, also based in Macon.
[src:1903-new-york-highlanders-season/1903-boston-americans-season] The Boston Americans played an exhibition game against Mercer University (with Cy Young pitching for Mercer) on March 23; the outcome being a 13─2 victory for Boston.
[src:1903-new-york-highlanders-season/1903-boston-americans-season] The team's longest losing streak was three games, which occurred twice; April 20–23 and September 22–23.
[src:1903-new-york-highlanders-season/1903-boston-americans-season] The team's longest game was 12 innings, which occurred three times.
[src:1903-new-york-highlanders-season/1903-boston-americans-season] The offense was led by Buck Freeman, who hit 13 home runs and had 104 RBIs, and Patsy Dougherty with a .331 batting average.
[src:1903-new-york-highlanders-season/1903-boston-americans-season] It was Freeman's third consecutive season with at least 100 RBIs.
[src:1903-new-york-highlanders-season/1903-boston-americans-season] The pitching staff was led by Cy Young, who made 40 appearances (35 starts) and pitched 34 complete games with a 28–9 record and 2.08 ERA, while striking out 176 in 341+2⁄3 innings.
[src:1903-new-york-highlanders-season/1903-boston-americans-season] The team had two other 20-game winners; Bill Dinneen (21–13) and Tom Hughes (20–7).
[src:1903-new-york-highlanders-season/1903-boston-americans-season] The team had three games end in a tie; July 31 at Washington, August 29 at Washington, and September 25 vs.
[src:1903-new-york-highlanders-season/1903-boston-americans-season] Tie games are not counted in league standings, but player statistics during tie games are counted.
[src:1903-new-york-highlanders-season/1903-boston-americans-season] Boston had an 11-game winning streak from May 28 through June 8, to put themselves in the AL lead.
[src:1903-new-york-highlanders-season/1903-boston-americans-season] While they briefly fell into second place in mid-June, behind Philadelphia, Boston then won 9-of-10 to recapture the lead, which they held through the end of the season.
[src:1903-new-york-highlanders-season/1903-boston-americans-season] The Americans met the Pittsburgh Pirates in the first modern World Series, an agreement between the AL and the NL as a post-season tournament.
[src:1903-new-york-highlanders-season/1903-boston-americans-season] The "Amerks" won the best-of-nine series in eight games; after falling behind, 3–1, they won four games in a row, clinching the championship at their home field, the Huntington Avenue Grounds, in Boston.
[src:1903-new-york-highlanders-season/1903-boston-beaneaters-season] The **1903 Boston Beaneaters season** was the 33rd season of the franchise.
[src:1903-new-york-highlanders-season/1903-boston-beaneaters-season] The team finished sixth in the National League with a record of 58–80, 32 games behind the Pittsburgh Pirates.
[src:1903-new-york-highlanders-season/1903-brooklyn-superbas-season] The **1903 Brooklyn Superbas season** was a season in Major League Baseball.
[src:1903-new-york-highlanders-season/1903-brooklyn-superbas-season] The Superbas began their slide from contention in the National League by finishing in fifth place.
[src:1903-new-york-highlanders-season/1903-chicago-cubs-season] The **1903 Chicago Cubs season** was the 32nd season of the Chicago Cubs franchise, the 28th in the National League, and the 11th at West Side Park.
[src:1903-new-york-highlanders-season/1903-chicago-cubs-season] The Cubs finished third in the National League with a record of 82–56.
[src:1903-new-york-highlanders-season/1903-chicago-cubs-season] On September 18, 1903, the Phillies' Chick Fraser pitched a no-hitter in the second game of a double header against the Cubs at West Side Park.
[src:1903-new-york-highlanders-season/1903-chicago-cubs-season] Fraser walked five batters, the Phillies committed four errors and won 10 to 0.
[src:1903-new-york-highlanders-season/1903-cincinnati-reds-season] The **1903 Cincinnati Reds season** was a season in American baseball.
[src:1903-new-york-highlanders-season/1903-cincinnati-reds-season] The team finished fourth in the National League with a record of 74–65, 16½ games behind the Pittsburgh Pirates.
[src:1903-new-york-highlanders-season/1903-cincinnati-reds-season] After a successful 1902 season in which the Reds finished the season at .500 after finishing in last place in 1901, Cincinnati was looking to continue their improvement.
[src:1903-new-york-highlanders-season/1903-cincinnati-reds-season] Joe Kelley, who took over as player-manager with sixty games remaining during the previous season, began his first full season with the team.
[src:1903-new-york-highlanders-season/1903-cincinnati-reds-season] During the off-season, forty-year-old outfielder Dummy Hoy retired.
[src:1903-new-york-highlanders-season/1903-cincinnati-reds-season] Hoy had played with the Reds from 1894 to 1897, before returning to the team for his final season in 1902.
[src:1903-new-york-highlanders-season/1903-cincinnati-reds-season] Twenty-five-year-old Mike Donlin took over for Hoy.
[src:1903-new-york-highlanders-season/1903-cincinnati-reds-season] Donlin had appeared in only 34 games with the Reds in 1902, but as a regular with the Baltimore Orioles of the American League in 1901, he hit .340 with five homers and 67 RBI.
[src:1903-new-york-highlanders-season/1903-cincinnati-reds-season] In his first full season with the team, Donlin hit a team high .351 with seven home runs and 67 RBI, while scoring 110 runs.
[src:1903-new-york-highlanders-season/1903-cincinnati-reds-season] Cy Seymour, also in his first full season with the Reds, hit .342 with seven homers and 72 RBI.
[src:1903-new-york-highlanders-season/1903-cincinnati-reds-season] Jake Beckley had another solid year, with a .327 batting average, two home runs and 81 RBI.
[src:1903-new-york-highlanders-season/1903-cincinnati-reds-season] Harry Steinfeldt hit .312 with six home runs and a club high 83 RBI, while player-manager Kelley batted .316 with three homers and 45 RBI.
[src:1903-new-york-highlanders-season/1903-cincinnati-reds-season] On the mound, Noodles Hahn led the way, going 22–12 with a 2.52 ERA in 34 starts, completing all of them.
[src:1903-new-york-highlanders-season/1903-cincinnati-reds-season] Jack Sutthoff was a surprise, going 16–9 with a 2.80 ERA in 30 games after spending the 1902 season in the minors with the Indianapolis Indians of the American Association.
[src:1903-new-york-highlanders-season/1903-cincinnati-reds-season] Cincinnati got off to a very slow start, losing eight of their first nine games to quickly fall into the National League cellar, 5.5 games out of first.
[src:1903-new-york-highlanders-season/1903-cincinnati-reds-season] The Reds rebounded by winning six of their next seven, then they hovered around the .500 in fourth place for pretty much the entire season after that.
[src:1903-new-york-highlanders-season/1903-cincinnati-reds-season] With their record at 44–43, the team managed to go 30–22 over their last fifty-two games to finish the season in fourth place at 74–65, which was their best record since going 83–67 in 1899, 16.5 games behind the pennant-winning Pittsburgh Pirates.
[src:1903-new-york-highlanders-season/1903-cleveland-naps-season] The **1903 Cleveland Naps season** was the third Major League Baseball season for the Cleveland American League team.
[src:1903-new-york-highlanders-season/1903-cleveland-naps-season] After two seasons as the Bluebirds or Blues and also being called the Bronchos (or Broncos) in 1902, beginning with the 1903 season, the team was called the Naps in honor of star second baseman Nap Lajoie.
[src:1903-new-york-highlanders-season/1903-cleveland-naps-season] The team finished third in the league with a record of 77–63, 15 games behind the Boston Americans.
[src:1903-new-york-highlanders-season/1903-new-york-highlanders-season] The New York Highlanders' 1903 season was the team's first.
[src:1903-new-york-highlanders-season/1903-new-york-highlanders-season] The team was founded as a replacement in the American League for the defunct Baltimore Orioles, was managed by Clark Griffith and played its home games at Hilltop Park (formally "American League Park").
[src:1903-new-york-highlanders-season/1903-new-york-highlanders-season] The club was at first officially the "Greater New York" baseball club, in deference to the established New York Giants, which were based in the Polo Grounds.
[src:1903-new-york-highlanders-season/1903-new-york-highlanders-season] This was the first season for the franchise that would be later known as the now-storied New York Yankees.
[src:1903-new-york-highlanders-season/1903-new-york-highlanders-season] They finished in 4th place in the AL with a record of 72–62.
[src:1903-new-york-highlanders-season/1903-new-york-highlanders-season] "Highlanders" was also originally short for "Gordon's Highlanders", a play on the name of the team President during 1903–1906, Joseph Gordon, along with the noted British military unit called The Gordon Highlanders.
[src:1903-new-york-highlanders-season/1903-new-york-highlanders-season] The club was also derisively called "Invaders" in 1903, presumably by writers favorable to the Giants.
[src:1903-new-york-highlanders-season/1903-new-york-highlanders-season] The New York press was creative with analogous nicknames for teams.
[src:1903-new-york-highlanders-season/1903-new-york-highlanders-season] In addition to "Highlanders", the team would soon acquire the alternate nickname "Yankees", the name that would soon become official and more famous among baseball fans in the coming decades.
[src:1903-new-york-highlanders-season/1903-new-york-highlanders-season] That word is a synonym for "American" in general, and short for American Leaguers or "Americans" in this case.
[src:1903-new-york-highlanders-season/1903-new-york-highlanders-season] Given the media's penchant for citing popular culture, that nickname was also possibly influenced by the then-current and hugely popular America-centric George M.
[src:1903-new-york-highlanders-season/1903-new-york-highlanders-season] Cohan Broadway play, "Little Johnny Jones", and its centerpiece song, "Yankee Doodle Dandy".
[src:1903-new-york-highlanders-season/1903-new-york-highlanders-season] New York writers had similarly coined both the established nickname Brooklyn "[Trolley] Dodgers" and the nickname "Superbas" that the denizens of Flatbush carried for a while.
[src:1903-new-york-highlanders-season/1903-new-york-highlanders-season] As with the Highlanders, the latter was based on something unrelated, namely a circus act called "Hanlon's Superbas"; the Dodgers were managed by Ned Hanlon at that time.
